Say, I have a plugin A, which has declared an optional OSGi dependency on a package from plugin B: 

{{Import-Package: plugin.B.api;version="4";resolution:=optional}}

Let's say plugin B version 3 is installed, so the dependency is not resolved and plugin A functions without interaction with plugin B.

Now the admin upgrades B from 3 to 4. The new version exports packages required by A, but the dependencies for A has already been resolved. Plugin A still does not interact with B, although it could. Furthermore, JIRA administrator may not know the reason why plugin A does not work with plugin B, if that's something they expect.

Disabling and then enabling plugin A does not help - the bundle is not re-resolved. The only things that help are: a) JIRA restart; b) Uninstallation/installtion of plugin B.

I suggest to add manual button in the UPM that will force plugin into disabled state, re-resolve the bundle, and enable plugin back.

Also the questionable dependencies can be detected automatically and the system could suggest the admin to re-resolve plugin A after upgrade of plugin B.

